issue_body:
with short reads, the default parallelization isn't keeping more than 3 of 4 cores busy most of the time.

It seems to improve quite a bit by bumping the batch size. I tried doing this from the command-line with K, but I think maybe it gets overridden by the `-x sr` opts?

If I modify the source as below, it keeps more cores (tested on 12 cpus)  busy for a higher percentage of time.


```Patch
diff --git a/map.c b/map.c
index ac66e81..2273d32 100644
--- a/map.c
+++ b/map.c
@@ -98,7 +98,7 @@ int mm_set_opt(const char *preset, mm_idxopt_t *io, mm_mapopt_t *mo)
                mo->best_n = 20;
                mo->mid_occ = 1000;
                mo->max_occ = 5000;
-               mo->mini_batch_size = 50000000;
+               mo->mini_batch_size = 250000000;
        } else if (strcmp(preset, "splice") == 0 || strcmp(preset, "cdna") == 0) {
                io->is_hpc = 0, io->k = 15, io->w = 5;
                mo->flag |= MM_F_SPLICE | MM_F_SPLICE_FOR | MM_F_SPLICE_REV;

```

On Debian 8.2 (jessie), pip (from `python-pip` package) places the files from `modules` folder under `/usr/local/share/yang/modules`.

Since pyang rely on `sys.prefix` to discover the location for default modules (ietf & iana), it incorrectly assumes the default installation directory as `/usr/share/yang/modules`. Therefore, **it cannot find common modules (implicit `$YANG_MODPATH`),  e.g. `ietf-yang-types`, resulting in errors**.

These errors can be replicated with the following procedure.
- Install the most recent version of pyang using pip (from git repo):

``` bash
cd /tmp
git clone https://github.com/mbj4668/pyang.git
cd pyang
python setup.py bdist_wheel
sudo pip install dist/pyang-1.6-py2.py3-none-any.whl
```
- Create an `example-sport.yang` file (based on [wikipedia example](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YANG#Example))

``` yang
module example-sports {
  namespace "http://example.com/example-sports";
  prefix sports;

  import ietf-yang-types {
    prefix yang;
  }

  container sports {
    config true;
    list person {
      key "name";
      leaf name {
        type string;
      }
      leaf birthday {
        type yang:date-and-time;
        mandatory true;
      }
    }
  }
}
```
- Compile the module

``` shell
pyang -f yin example-sports.yang -o example-sports.yin
# => example-sports.yang:5: error: module "ietf-yang-types" not found in search path
```

The following information describes the system state

``` bash
which python
# => /usr/bin/python
python -V
# => Python 2.7.9
python -c 'import sys; print sys.prefix'
# => /usr
which pyang
# => /usr/local/bin/pyang
ls /usr/share/yang/
# => ls: cannot access /usr/share/yang/: No such file or directory
ls /usr/local/share/yang/
# => schema/   modules/   xslt/   images/
```

Note that, when `import` statement is removed and `yang:date-and-time` is changed to `string`, the module compiles without problem.

I think this behavior cannot be detected in CI tests, since travis uses `env.sh`, which explicitly defines `$YANG_MODPATH`

I'm trying to replicate a small arduino sketch using PyMata. I was wondering if you could offer any insight into the following two programs for a motor controller. The code is suppose to set a speed using analog pin 10 and then set a direction for the motor by setting pins 12 and 13 on or off. The first one (arduino) works correctly. However, the second one in python is only partially working (the forwards and reverse LEDs on the motor controller light up correctly but the motors do not move). Because the lights are toggling, my theory is that there is that the issue resides in my analog write to pin 10.

```arduino
int rm1 = 12;
int rm2 = 13;
int rms = 10;

void setup() {
  pinMode(rm1,OUTPUT);
  pinMode(rm2,OUTPUT);
  pinMode(rms,OUTPUT);

  analogWrite(rms, 255);
}

void loop() {
  digitalWrite(rm1, LOW);
  digitalWrite(rm2, HIGH);
  
  delay(2000);
  
  digitalWrite(rm1, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(rm2, LOW);
  
  delay(2000);
}
```

```python
from PyMata.pymata import PyMata
import signal
import time
import sys


def signal_handler(sig, frame):
    print('You pressed Ctrl+C!!!!')
    if board is not None:
        board.reset()
    sys.exit(0)


signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, signal_handler)
board = PyMata('/dev/ttyACM0')

rm1 = 12
rm2 = 13
rms = 10

board.set_pin_mode(rms, board.OUTPUT, board.ANALOG)
board.set_pin_mode(rm1, board.OUTPUT, board.DIGITAL)
board.set_pin_mode(rm2, board.OUTPUT, board.DIGITAL)

board.analog_write(rms, 255);

while True:
    board.digital_write(rm1, 0);
    board.digital_write(rm2, 1);

    time.sleep(1)

    board.digital_write(rm1, 1);
    board.digital_write(rm2, 0);

    time.sleep(1)
```

