fontmake currently has a “preprocess” function to handle glyph names with hyphens. (In Glyphs files, glyphs can contain hyphens in their names, but hyphens are not valid in Adobe feature files).

However, the current implementation is **extremely** fragile: It tries to extract glyph names from the glyphs source, under the (wrong) assumption that anything with a `name` property in the Glyphs source is probably a glyph. Then, it just runs a string replace on the entire input, in the (wrong) hope that those rewrites won’t affect anything else but the glyph name.

An example where this doesn’t work is https://github.com/googlei18n/fontmake/issues/247. Here, the font contained the following (abbreviated) dictionary with TrueType hinting zones. fontmake wrongly recognizes the string “B: -219” as a glyph name, rewrites it to “B: .219”, and then it shoves it into glyphsLib.

```p
{
name = TTFZones;
value = (
{
name = "B: 0";
position = 0;
size = -15;
},
{
name = "B: -219";
position = -219;
size = -18;
}
);
```

Instead of doing such hackery, I think fontmake should pass the original, unmodified glyphs file to glyphsLib. It’s the task of glyphsLib to deal with valid input Glyphs files, and convert this to valid UFO with valid OpenType feature files. Therefore, it’s clearly within the scope of glyphsLib to know what constitutes a valid glyph name in what file format. Of course it’s necessary to handle this unfortunate mismatch, but for doing this correctly, one needs to parse the file. So the place for doing such rewrites should be glyphsLib and not fontmake.

